english:
  title: Preface to the Collected Poems of Yu Geukgi
  author: Sung Hyun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Poetry is difficult to speak of. Those who discourse on poetry but discuss only its vital force while neglecting its underlying principle err greatly. Vital force manifests outwardly, while principle abides within. When what dwells within lacks firmness, one cannot escape waywardness and dishonest invention. Thus poetry values principle above all. The skilled poet awakens to principle, and so preserves the root. Should one lose the root, then no matter how bold, how beautiful, how extravagantly adorned—all manner of flourish—it cannot truly be called poetry. From the late Koryŏ through our present dynasty, poetry has not lacked celebrated masters, yet few have truly grasped its principle. Thus the plain fall into rusticity, the bold into excess, the strange into barrenness, the clever into fragmentation. These habits have gradually declined into weakness from which there is no return. Alas, this is poetry's misfortune.

    Commissioner Yu, whose virtue lies in self-conquest, is a distinguished scholar of the palace. In his youth he studied poetry under Master Chŏmbil, who gained renown through his verse, drawing countless followers eager to bask in his reflected glory. I too was acquainted with the master, and whenever he spoke of talented individuals, he praised Commissioner Yu as remarkable. Later, when I entered the Hall of Worthies, I spent considerable time in the Commissioner's company. Listening to his discourse and savoring his poems, I found that his work penetrated principle through personal discovery. Thus each piece bears proper form, each line strikes with force. Though refined and cultivated, his work never descends into worldly convention—like an autumn mountain of protruding bone and sparse flesh, endlessly jagged and austere, yet with vegetation equally hardy and firm. Does he not inherit the lingering resonance of the elegiac and laudatory styles of old?

    Once, the sage of Jurok studied the Great Mystery and Method Words under Yang Xiong, yet Liu Xin upon reading them said, "I fear posterity will use this to cover sauce jars." Yan You asked Huan Tan, "Can Yang Xiong's writings survive to future ages?" Tan replied, "Common people esteem the distant and despise the near. Seeing Zi Yun in person—his rank and bearing move no one—they dismiss his work as worthless." From Yang Xiong's death until now, forty years have passed before his writings were recognized. In that time, Xiong was little known and little valued; only the sage studied with him and only Tan admired him. Yet still the current flowed far and did not perish. How much more so with Commissioner Yu, whom Chŏmbil praised and whom the royal court deeply endorsed, whose words are spoken in every mouth? That his work shall not cover sauce jars is manifest.

    When we say poetry confines a person, we mean obscurity robs him of recognition by the ruler of his age. Commissioner Yu, though he encountered an enlightened era and received the regard of a sage-king, remained unfulfilled. Truly, poetry confines a person. The Commissioner's official titles and deeds cannot be inscribed in history's pages, yet what endures is his poetry alone. How then can we not preserve it in print? Seeing his remaining work, I weep, and thus write this preface.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Chŏmbil (佔畢) refers to Kim Jongjik (金宗直), an influential fifteenth-century Korean poet and scholar
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to Yang Xiong and Liu Xin alludes to the delayed recognition of profound works, suggesting Yu's poetry will be similarly vindicated by posterity
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Hall of Worthies' (홍문관) was Korea's highest scholarly institution during the Chosŏn dynasty
  - key: ''
    value: Yu Geukgi served under King Sŏngjong but faced political difficulties; this preface suggests that despite royal recognition, true fulfillment eluded him
